WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.125 --> 00:00:04.644
Flail chest is a life-threatening chest
wall injury where multiple adjacent ribs are

2
00:00:04.644 --> 00:00:07.545
fractured in at least two places, creating
a free-floating

3
00:00:07.545 --> 00:00:09.125
segment of the thoracic cage.

4
00:00:09.765 --> 00:00:13.524
Instead of moving outward during
inspiration, this unstable segment moves

5
00:00:13.524 --> 00:00:16.225
inward, a phenomenon called paradoxical
movement.

6
00:00:16.424 --> 00:00:20.805
This disrupts normal ventilation and
significantly increases the work of breathing.

7
00:00:20.864 --> 00:00:23.485
But the real danger is not just the rib
fractures,

8
00:00:23.604 --> 00:00:25.844
it's the underlying pulmonary contusion.

9
00:00:26.405 --> 00:00:30.045
The lung tissue beneath the injury becomes
bruised, edematous,

10
00:00:30.165 --> 00:00:33.064
and filled with fluid, leading to
decreased compliance,

11
00:00:33.625 --> 00:00:36.604
impaired gas exchange, and worsening
oxygenation over time.

12
00:00:36.705 --> 00:00:41.465
That means patients may initially appear
stable but deteriorate hours later.

13
00:00:42.264 --> 00:00:44.264
Clinically, these patients present with
chest pain,

14
00:00:44.784 --> 00:00:47.665
shallow breathing, tachypnea, and visible
paradoxical

15
00:00:47.665 --> 00:00:48.305
chest movement.

16
00:00:49.104 --> 00:00:52.625
Breath sounds may be diminished, and
oxygen saturation often drops

17
00:00:52.625 --> 00:00:55.005
as perfusion mismatch worsens.

18
00:00:55.705 --> 00:00:58.165
As an RT, your assessment should focus on
work of

19
00:00:58.165 --> 00:01:00.264
breathing, air movement, oxygenation,

20
00:01:00.365 --> 00:01:01.345
and signs of fatigue.

21
00:01:02.104 --> 00:01:05.404
Diagnostics typically include chest x-ray,
but CT scan is

22
00:01:05.404 --> 00:01:09.025
more sensitive and can better identify rib
fractures and pulmonary contusion.

23
00:01:09.824 --> 00:01:15.245
ABGs may initially show mild hypoxemia but
can progress to respiratory failure if not

24
00:01:15.245 --> 00:01:16.004
managed aggressively.

25
00:01:16.724 --> 00:01:19.785
Management focuses on three priorities,
oxygenation,

26
00:01:20.165 --> 00:01:21.985
pain control, and ventilatory support.

27
00:01:21.985 --> 00:01:25.824
Oxygen therapy is essential, but adequate
pain control is critical

28
00:01:25.824 --> 00:01:29.525
because if the patient can't breathe
deeply, they will hypoventilate

29
00:01:29.525 --> 00:01:31.504
and develop atelectasis or pneumonia.

30
00:01:31.864 --> 00:01:36.044
This is why regional anesthesia or
epidural analgesia is often preferred.

31
00:01:36.285 --> 00:01:40.485
For patients with increasing work of
breathing or hypoxemia, non-

32
00:01:40.485 --> 00:01:44.205
invasive ventilation may be used, but many
will require intubation

33
00:01:44.205 --> 00:01:45.425
and mechanical ventilation.

34
00:01:46.084 --> 00:01:51.065
In these cases, positive pressure
ventilation stabilizes the internally and

35
00:01:51.065 --> 00:01:52.404
improves oxygenation.

36
00:01:53.065 --> 00:01:56.864
Red flags include worsening hypoxemia,
rising PaCO2,

37
00:01:57.324 --> 00:01:59.584
fatigue, altered mental status, and
decreasing

38
00:01:59.584 --> 00:02:00.184
air movement.

39
00:02:00.525 --> 00:02:04.464
These signal impending respiratory failure
and the need for rapid escalation.

40
00:02:05.065 --> 00:02:07.425
From an RT perspective, your role is
critical,

41
00:02:08.285 --> 00:02:11.244
monitoring ventilation and oxygenation,
supporting airway clearance,

42
00:02:12.184 --> 00:02:15.804
optimizing ventilator settings, and
recognizing early signs of deterioration.

43
00:02:16.324 --> 00:02:19.664
Bottom line, flail chest is both a
mechanical and pulmonary

44
00:02:19.664 --> 00:02:20.205
problem.

45
00:02:20.884 --> 00:02:23.104
Treat the pain, support ventilation, and

46
00:02:23.104 --> 00:02:25.244
always watch for delayed respiratory
decline.

